<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">Scrabble Triple Word Score Strategy — Reaching & Using TWS</h1>

<p>Triple Word Score squares are the most powerful positions on the Scrabble board. A single well-placed word on a TWS can swing a game by 60+ points. Mastering when to reach for them, when to block them, and how to combine them with high-value tiles separates intermediate players from experts.</p>

<!-- Stat Strip -->
<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
  <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4 text-center">
    <div><span class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">8</span><br><span class="text-sm text-gray-400">TWS squares on board</span></div>
    <div><span class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">3×</span><br><span class="text-sm text-gray-400">word score multiplier</span></div>
    <div><span class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">9×</span><br><span class="text-sm text-gray-400">max with triple-triple</span></div>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">TWS Square Positions</h2>

<p>The 8 Triple Word Score squares are arranged symmetrically at the outer edges and corners of the 15×15 board:</p>

<table class="w-full text-sm my-4">
  <thead><tr class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800"><th class="p-2 text-left">Position</th><th class="p-2 text-left">Coordinates</th><th class="p-2 text-left">Access Difficulty</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="p-2">Top-left corner</td><td class="p-2">1A</td><td class="p-2">Hard — requires 7+ letter reach</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2">Top-right corner</td><td class="p-2">1O</td><td class="p-2">Hard — same corner difficulty</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="p-2">Bottom-left corner</td><td class="p-2">15A</td><td class="p-2">Hard — often reached in endgame</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2">Bottom-right corner</td><td class="p-2">15O</td><td class="p-2">Hard — rarely accessed early</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="p-2">Top-middle</td><td class="p-2">1H</td><td class="p-2">Medium — 7 squares from centre</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2">Bottom-middle</td><td class="p-2">15H</td><td class="p-2">Medium — mirror of top</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="p-2">Left-middle</td><td class="p-2">8A</td><td class="p-2">Medium — directly left of centre</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2">Right-middle</td><td class="p-2">8O</td><td class="p-2">Medium — directly right of centre</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">How to Reach TWS Squares</h2>

<p>Getting to a TWS requires planning 2-3 turns ahead. Here are the primary access routes:</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">The Ladder Approach</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Build words incrementally toward the edge. Place a 4-letter word, then extend toward the TWS on your next turn.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-400 mb-2">The Bingo Stretch</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">A 7-letter word from centre reaches the edge TWS squares directly. Plan bingos to land on row 1, 15, column A, or O.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-purple-400 mb-2">The Hook Extension</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Hook an existing word near the edge. Adding an S or prefix/suffix can reach a TWS without using all 7 tiles.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-400 mb-2">Parallel Play</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Play a word parallel to an existing edge word, letting your final tile land on TWS. Creates multiple scoring words simultaneously.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">When to Block Opponents</h2>

<p>Defence is just as important as offence. Blocking a TWS your opponent is targeting can save 40+ points:</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
  <p class="text-sm text-purple-300"><strong class="text-purple-400">Blocking Rule:</strong> If your opponent's last word is within 3 squares of a TWS, assume they're aiming for it. Place a short word that occupies the critical squares between their word and the TWS.</p>
</div>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Dead-end blocking</strong> — place a word ending with an uncommon letter (V, J, Q) next to the TWS so extending through it is nearly impossible</li>
  <li><strong>Sacrifice blocking</strong> — play a low-scoring word specifically to prevent a high-scoring TWS play. A 12-point block that prevents a 45-point TWS play is a net gain of 33</li>
  <li><strong>Congestion blocking</strong> — fill the area around the TWS with short perpendicular words, making it impossible to build a long word through it</li>
  <li><strong>Pre-emptive blocking</strong> — early in the game, avoid opening lines that lead to corner TWS squares</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Combining TWS with High-Value Tiles</h2>

<p>The real power of TWS comes from combining it with premium letter tiles:</p>

<table class="w-full text-sm my-4">
  <thead><tr class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800"><th class="p-2 text-left">Tile on TWS</th><th class="p-2 text-left">Base Points</th><th class="p-2 text-left">After 3× Word</th><th class="p-2 text-left">Example Word (tripled)</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="p-2 font-mono">Z (10)</td><td class="p-2">10</td><td class="p-2">30+</td><td class="p-2">ZAP = 42 pts</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2 font-mono">Q (10)</td><td class="p-2">10</td><td class="p-2">30+</td><td class="p-2">QI = 33 pts</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="p-2 font-mono">X (8)</td><td class="p-2">8</td><td class="p-2">24+</td><td class="p-2">AX = 27 pts</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2 font-mono">J (8)</td><td class="p-2">8</td><td class="p-2">24+</td><td class="p-2">JO = 27 pts</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
  <p class="text-sm text-purple-300"><strong class="text-purple-400">Advanced Tip:</strong> If a Double Letter Score (DLS) square sits on the same word as a TWS, the letter bonus applies FIRST, then the entire word is tripled. A Z on DLS in a TWS word scores: (10×2)×3 = 60 points just for that letter's contribution.</p>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Triple-Triple — Scrabble's Holy Grail</h2>

<p>A triple-triple occurs when a single word covers TWO Triple Word Score squares simultaneously. The word score is multiplied by 3, then by 3 again — meaning ×9 total. This is the single highest-scoring play possible in Scrabble.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-400 mb-2">Requirements</h3>
    <ul class="text-sm text-gray-300 list-disc pl-4 space-y-1">
      <li>Word must span from one TWS to another</li>
      <li>Both TWS squares must be unused (fresh)</li>
      <li>Usually requires a 7+ letter word (bingo)</li>
      <li>Only possible on rows 1, 8, 15 or columns A, H, O</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">Potential Scores</h3>
    <ul class="text-sm text-gray-300 list-disc pl-4 space-y-1">
      <li>Average bingo (75 pts) × 9 = 675+ pts</li>
      <li>Add 50-point bingo bonus = 725+ total</li>
      <li>Theoretical max single play: 1,778 pts</li>
      <li>Realistic max in play: 300-500 pts</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Defensive Blocking Strategies</h2>

<p>The best defence against TWS is controlling board openness. Here's when to prioritise blocking over scoring:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>You're ahead by 30+ points</strong> — protect your lead by blocking open TWS lanes</li>
  <li><strong>Opponent has a strong rack</strong> — if they're holding tiles after a big draw, block aggressively</li>
  <li><strong>Late game (fewer than 20 tiles left)</strong> — every point matters, prevent comeback plays</li>
  <li><strong>Corner TWS untouched</strong> — if both corners on a side are open, one play could hit a triple-triple</li>
</ul>

